      <p>
        These are extracts of some of the films I've worked on.
      </p>
      <p>
        INTRO -  Chaly's World: The protagonist wakes up and finds herself absorbed by a TV. All the Sound Design for Chaly's World was made in 24 hours.
      </p>
      <p>
        1) MY BEST FRIEND (0:41): As they watch Betty Boop cartoons, the protagonist, a teenage girl, is pressured into drinking by her best friend and a much older man, who scarcely hides his foul intentions. The sound here, on the one hand, is meant to enhance the threat that he represents, foreshadowing what is about to come later on. On the other hand, it's very subjective to the point of view of the protagonist. Subtle sounds are prioritised.
      </p>
      <p>
        2) THE GRAD FILM (3:03): In this comedy, the production of a student film is falling apart. The scene is messy and relentless, with many characters constantly moving around, which caused a lot of issues with production sound. A lot of work was put into matching completely different sources capturing the dialogue and cleaning the tracks. Other than that, sound is there to help the comedic timing with big and small sound effects, sharp contrasts in volume, and help drawing our attention to the right part of the screen.
      </p>
      <p>
        3) WHEN I WAS A TEENAGE WHORE (6:04): A coming of age film about a teenager about to lose her virginity, this film needed the sound to add awkwardness to the build-up. This is accomplished by quiet moments, intimate sounds, and intentionally omitting sound effects, providing with a highly subjective experience. All of the dialogue is ADR.
      </p>
      <p>
        4) MADAME CAREY (9:51):  In this short film inspired by Madame Bovary, the character daydreams with a better, more interesting life, as she feels suffocated by her routine as a housewife. These dreams are conveyed mainly through sound. 
      </p>
